<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 16 日星期三 02:24:44 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[North Korea Makes First Public Comments About Detained U.S. Soldier Travis King]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>据称，金告诉调查人员，他因不人道的虐待和种族歧视而对美国怀有恶意<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001137985"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="549" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822956?width=860&amp;height=549" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国士兵特拉维斯·金上个月故意进入朝鲜。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ahn Young-joon/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001137985"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/timothy-w-martin" itemprop="url" rel="author">蒂莫西·W·马丁</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 6:51 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-makes-first-public-comments-about-detained-u-s-soldier-travis-king-48ace148"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>首尔——朝鲜首次就<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">扣押一名美国士兵</a>近一个月的情况发表公开评论，声称这名美国军人曾表示，他面临美国陆军的非人道虐待和种族歧视，并寻求金正恩政权的庇护。</p><p>朝鲜在周三的官方媒体报道中表示，二等兵特拉维斯·金<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-u-s-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在接受平壤当局调查时曾</a>表示希望逃离朝鲜或第三国“寻求庇护”。</p><p>官方媒体称，身为黑人的金据称告诉朝鲜调查人员，他对美国陆军“怀有敌意”，并且“对不平等的美国社会感到失望”。</p><p>朝鲜称金非法进入朝鲜，但没有具体说明这位 23 岁的美国军人可能面临什么惩罚。该报告没有提及金的健康状况，也没有提及他可能获释的时间表。官方媒体称，朝鲜的调查仍在进行中。</p><p>平壤<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-north-korea-start-talking-about-american-soldier-who-crossed-the-border-6be51607?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">此前曾通过军事热线向美国承认</a>其扣留了金。 7月18日，金在参观联合警备区时跨越朝韩两国军事分界线，故意进入朝鲜。</p><p> “我们无法核实这些所谓的评论，”五角大楼官员表示。 “我们仍然关注他的安全回归。该部门的首要任务是将二等兵国王带回家，我们正在通过所有可用的渠道努力实现这一结果。”</p><p>金是几十年来第一位自愿进入朝鲜的美国军人。在此前的此类事件中，平壤曾逼迫美国俘虏招供，迫使他们承认自己是间谍或并未犯下的罪行。</p><p>与此同时，朝鲜经常利用被拘留的美国士兵作为宣传工具。平壤选择将他们的叛逃视为金氏政权社会主义制度的优越性，同时说明美国的邪恶</p><p>根据朝鲜的说法，金于 7 月 18 日下午 3 点 30 分左右被拘留，拘留地点位于朝韩两国会面的边境大楼和朝鲜士兵的卫生间之间。</p><p>以美国为首的联合国司令部与朝鲜的接触有限。但美国官员表示，这些互动并不具有实质性。华盛顿与平壤缺乏直接的外交关系。因此，美国像以前一样，向瑞典寻求外展援助。</p><p>金在韩国面临袭击指控，并在韩国的拘留所里呆了近七周。他将登上返回美国的航班，在那里他将面临纪律处分并可能被开除。</p><p> 7月17日，他被护送至仁川机场，但他设法离开并登上了前往韩国最大旅游景点之一朝韩非军事区的旅游巴士。金的情况<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-soldiers-crossing-into-north-korea-points-to-security-gaps-576b7733?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">引发了人们对旅游景点安全措施的质疑</a>。</p><p>写信给 Timothy W. Martin，邮箱为<a href="mailto:Timothy.Martin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Timothy.Martin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 22:51:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-makes-first-public-comments-about-detained-us-soldier-travis-king-48ace148</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-makes-first-public-comments-about-detained-us-soldier-travis-king-48ace148<author><![CDATA[Timothy W. Martin]]></author><category>华尔街日报</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>歧视</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>种族主义/仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>歧视</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>种族主义</category><category>仇外心理</category><category>社会问题</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Georgia Case Presents Unique Challenges for Trump—and Prosecutors]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> RICO 的指控为检察官提供了向陪审团提供全面叙述的机会，但可能被证明难以处理<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135918"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835588?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乔治亚州富尔顿县地方检察官提起的指控称，唐纳德·特朗普参与了推翻 2020 年大选的犯罪活动。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布林·安德森/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135918"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/corinne-ramey" itemprop="url" rel="author">科琳·雷米</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-fanelli" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹姆斯·法内利</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 4:27（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/georgia-case-presents-unique-challenges-for-trumpand-prosecutors-4dd6ee37"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">佐治亚州</a>对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>敲诈勒索和其他十几项涉嫌犯罪的起诉是针对这位前总统最雄心勃勃、最全面的案件，并且可能对特朗普和检察官构成前所未有的法律挑战。</p><p>该案件由<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fani-willis-the-no-nonsense-georgia-prosecutor-on-a-collision-course-with-donald-trump-600b88f8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">富尔顿县地方检察官法</a>尼·威利斯 (Fani Willis) 提起，指控特朗普<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/who-are-trumps-co-defendants-in-the-georgia-rico-case-73b56354?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与其他 18 人</a>一起参与犯罪活动，以改变<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-election-grand-jury-georgia-voters-4cd64c0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2020 年总统选举</a>对他有利的方式，违反了该州的反敲诈勒索法。</p><p>特朗普否认有不当行为。这位前总统称威利斯有党派倾向，并表示他没有篡改选举。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>佐治亚州的法律以 1970 年联邦《诈骗影响和腐败组织法》为蓝本，该法为联邦检察官提供了一个新工具，通过将黑帮老大与其犯罪组织内下属的行为联系起来，追捕黑手党。在接下来的几十年里，纽约和其他地方的检察官<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rudy-giuliani-indicted-racketeering-trump-rico-e2339c94?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">成功地利用联邦 RICO 法</a>打倒了几个著名的黑手党家族和其他犯罪企业。</p><p>佐治亚州的法律在某些方面比联邦版本更广泛，因为它包括更长的基本犯罪清单，可以作为指控一组被告参与共同犯罪活动的基础。</p><p> “佐治亚州的 RICO 法规由于其范围广泛，允许检察官讲述整个故事：人物、事件、时间、地点和方式，”前迪卡尔布县地方检察官、现供职于律师事务所的格温·凯斯·弗莱明 (Gwen Keyes Fleming) 说欧华律师事务所派珀。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=63AF554A-ED80-41F6-BE4D-ADF5F7ECFA84&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fgeorgia-case-presents-unique-challenges-for-trumpand-prosecutors-4dd6ee37&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">前总统唐纳德·特朗普在州和联邦层面面临四项单独的起诉。 《华尔街日报》详细分析了每项起诉书及其对他 2024 年总统竞选的意义。摄影插图：赵安妮<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>特别检察官杰克·史密斯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-indictment-jack-smith-2020-election-4b351abf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">最近对特朗普涉嫌寻求推翻 2020 年大选的联邦起诉书</a>与佐治亚州案件有一些相同的主题，但采用了简洁、有针对性的方法。</p><p>相比之下， <a href="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/documents/GATRUMPINDICTMENT081423.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">威利斯的起诉书</a>按时间顺序提出了一系列所谓的“行为”，列出了一场巨大而庞大的颠覆选举的阴谋，特朗普被指控在政治上相当于黑帮老大。</p><p> “如果杰克·史密斯对特朗普的严厉控诉是海明威，那么法尼·威利斯对特朗普的控诉则是海明威。</p>布鲁金斯学会高级研究员诺姆·艾森说，这份涵盖 19 名被告、41 条指控的文件就是狄更斯。 “这与所谓的阴谋本身一样庞大和复杂。”<p></p><p>该计划的大量涉嫌参与者也可能给民主党人威利斯带来更多影响力。在典型的 RICO 案件中，检察官经常希望获得一些被告的认罪协议，以换取他们针对最引人注目的目标提供的证词。周一长达 98 页的起诉书表明，检察官已经有了合作证人，其中包括文件中指出的一些未被起诉的同谋者。</p><p>前亚特兰大美国律师兼 King &amp; Spalding 律师事务所合伙人约翰·霍恩 (John Horn) 表示，其他被告最终也可能决定合作，特别是当他们知道如果被定罪就无法立即获得赦免时。 “本案中主要被告面临的风险要大得多，”他说。</p><p>佐治亚州敲诈勒索法的另一个显着特点是：定罪后强制判处最低五年徒刑。</p><p> “如果他被定罪，他就会入狱，”前联邦检察官、亚特兰大刑事辩护律师杰里·弗罗利希 (Jerry Froelich) 说。</p><p>在过去的一些案件中，法官允许被定罪的被告至少部分服刑，而不是入狱服刑。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835762?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">周一，富尔顿县地方检察官法尼·威利斯在大陪审团对前总统唐纳德·特朗普及其盟友提出起诉后。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：ELIJAH NOUVELAGE/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>如果特朗普赢得下届总统选举，他可能会尝试在任何联邦案件中赦免自己，或引导司法部撤销对史密斯的指控。在佐治亚州，他没有能力消除州定罪或监禁。即使特朗普要寻求州赦免，他也只有在因任何定罪服刑后才有资格这样做。在佐治亚州，任何此类赦免都将由州委员会决定，而不是州长。</p><p>然而，威利斯也面临着挑战。她曾表示，她将寻求在未来六个月内进行审判，但辩护律师表示，这样的时间表可能不切实际。大量被告可能会导致审判安排陷入困境，从而延误任何诉讼程序。由于案件的政治性质和潜在审判的预期时间，陪审团的选择也可能会拖延数月。</p><p>弗吉尼亚州前美国律师小约翰·菲什威克 (John Fishwick Jr.) 表示：“联邦案件更有可能迅​​速进入审判阶段，而不会因多名被告和争论而陷入困境。”他说，乔治亚州的案件“是一个值得推迟的理想案件”。</p><p>另一个悬而未决的案件就说明了这一点。去年，威利斯对与街头暴力团伙有关联的 27 名被告提出了 56 项 RICO 起诉书。一些被告已接受认罪协议，但其余被告的陪审团遴选工作已于一月份开始，预计将再持续一两个月。审判预计需要六到九个月的时间。</p><p>亚特兰大的律师布莱恩·斯蒂尔 (Brian Steel) 代表杰弗里·威廉姆斯 (Jeffery Williams)，他更广为人知的名字是说唱歌手 Young Thug，他是该帮派案件的被告之一。 Steel 表示，RICO 对大量被告的起诉可能在后勤上具有挑战性，而且进展缓慢。他已经代表威廉姆斯对审前动议进行了数周的辩论，还有 50 项动议有待法官审理。 “那只是我，那只是我的客户，”斯蒂尔说。</p><p>特朗普可能会寻求将案件移交联邦法院，进一步推迟诉讼程序。此举需要法官的批准。这位前总统在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indictment-new-york-7e64e016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">纽约的起诉</a>中提出了类似的要求，涉及<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trumps-hush-money-a-history-of-the-wsjs-investigation-fccf8096?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">向一名色情明星支付封口费</a>。该申请被拒绝，理由是特朗普没有在所谓的封口费计划中履行总统职责。一些律师表示，特朗普可能有更有力的理由推动佐治亚州案件的审理，因为它与总统职位的关系更为直接。</p><p>在联邦法院进行审判对特朗普来说可能是一个优势，因为他可以从更多的县中选择陪审团，其中包括一些倾向于共和党的县。 “在富尔顿县，这是一个相当民主党的县，而且陪审团池非常有限，”弗罗利希说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835590?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在这张法庭素描中，前总统唐纳德·特朗普在本月早些时候的认罪听证会上在联邦法院宣誓，罪名是他策划了一场阴谋，试图推翻自己在 2020 年选举中的失败。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：简·罗森伯格/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>特朗普现已在四起不同案件中被起诉，他于四月份在纽约首次受到指控。曼哈顿地区检察官阿尔文·布拉格 (Alvin Bragg) 指控他犯有 34 项伪造商业记录的重罪，指控他精心策划了一项计划，通过支付封口费来压制可能具有破坏性的性指控，以支持他 2016 年的总统竞选活动。作为初犯，如果在此案中被定罪，他不太可能面临牢狱之灾。</p><p>特朗普<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-associate-also-indicted-in-mar-a-lago-documents-case-759cbb17?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在六月份受到了他的第一次联邦指控，</a>当时史密斯声称他保留了他知道离开白宫后不应该保留的机密文件。史密斯<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-lawyers-jack-smith-jan-6-58c2fd14" target="_blank" class="icon none">后来补充说</a>，特朗普和他的助手试图删除他的海湖庄园俱乐部的监控录像，以免将其移交给大陪审团。</p><p>特别检察官本月提起了他的另一起更广泛的案件，指控特朗普密谋推翻 2020 年选举结果以继续掌权。</p><p> 2024 年<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sizing-up-the-2024-republican-primary-field-db34a150" target="_blank" class="icon none">共和党总统提名</a>的领先者特朗普对其他起诉书表示无罪，并指责检察官试图干涉他的选举前景。</p><p>写信给 Corinne Ramey ( <a href="mailto:corinne.ramey@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">corinne.ramey@wsj.com)</a>和 James Fanelli ( <a href="mailto:james.fanelli@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">james.fanelli@wsj.com</a> ) </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/537f22eb-7442-4360-8305-39f89aae3339.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 20:27:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/georgia-case-presents-unique-challenges-for-trumpand-prosecutors-4dd6ee37</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/georgia-case-presents-unique-challenges-for-trumpand-prosecutors-4dd6ee37<author><![CDATA[Corinne RameyJames Fanelli]]></author><category>特朗普法律</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>特朗普法律</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>唐纳德·特朗普</category><category>法尼·威利斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. in Talks to Develop Ukraine’s Grain Export Routes]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>俄罗斯退出安全协议后，与土耳其、基辅和其他国家的讨论重点是未来收成的替代渠道<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001136525"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835934?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">罗马尼亚康斯坦察黑海港的一个粮食码头是乌克兰出口的中转站。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：daniel mihailescu/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001136525"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jared-malsin" itemprop="url" rel="author">贾里德·马尔辛</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦斯·诺曼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日下午 1:15 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-in-talks-to-develop-ukraine-grain-export-routes-3e597c3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伊斯坦布尔——官员们表示，在俄罗斯退出<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/great-power-rivalry-looms-over-ukraine-grain-deal-3d2e0eb1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">保证黑海食品运输安全的</a>协议后，美国正在与土耳其、乌克兰和基辅邻国进行谈判，以增加乌克兰谷物替代出口路线的使用。</p><p>美国支持的计划包括增加乌克兰在 10 月份之前每月通过多瑙河出口 400 万吨粮食的能力。大部分谷物将顺河而下，经黑海运往罗马尼亚附近的港口，然后运往其他目的地。尽管速度较慢且成本较高，但这条航线将作为去年根据与俄罗斯、土耳其和联合国达成的协议建立的黑海航运走廊的替代方案。</p><p>俄罗斯于 7 月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/why-russia-killed-the-ukraine-grain-deal-faf1f8c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">退出该协议</a>，导致乌克兰从敖德萨周围三个港口的出口停止，并导致黑海冲突升级。最近几周，俄罗斯军队对乌克兰港口<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-strikes-odesa-port-after-quitting-black-sea-grain-deal-4df967bd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">发动了一波导弹和无人机袭击</a>，并于周日登上了一艘前往乌克兰的商船。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="736" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/313c2c2b-ee53-4b10-925e-6cac55c527ff-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>西方对黑海粮食计划替代方案的规划表明，美国、乌克兰和欧洲国家正在为俄罗斯未能及时重新加入该协议以转移乌克兰夏季和秋季收成的情况做准备。</p><p>一位驻华盛顿的美国高级官员表示：“现实情况是，俄罗斯已决定攻击全球粮食供应，在它认为攻击结束之前，很难将其挽回。”</p><p>由于乌克兰是小麦、玉米和葵花籽油的最大出口国，因此粮食协议被认为对于保持全球低食品价格至关重要。据美国国务院称，自俄罗斯上个月退出黑海协议以来，食品价格已上涨 10%。联合国称，俄罗斯入侵乌克兰是近年来导致世界各地数百万人濒临饥饿的一系列危机之一</p><p>官员们表示，在努力增加乌克兰通过多瑙河的出口能力的同时，土耳其和联合国也在努力说服俄罗斯重新加入粮食协议。外交官称，去年帮助促成该协议的土耳其总统雷杰普·塔伊普·埃尔多安面临着在乌克兰收获的谷物于 9 月初开始堆积之前恢复该协议的压力。</p><p>这位华盛顿官员表示，美国正在考虑所有可能的选择，包括军事解决方案，以保护进出乌克兰多瑙河港口的船只，但拒绝透露这些选择的具体细节，也拒绝透露哪些国家将参与其中。</p><p> “我们将考虑一切，”这位官员在谈到保护航道的努力时说道。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="470" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835927?width=700&amp;height=470" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7月底，运粮卡车等待进入罗马尼亚康斯坦察港口。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：daniel mihailescu/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国国务院表示，美国高级官员周五在罗马尼亚加拉茨市举行的一次会议上与乌克兰、摩尔多瓦和北大西洋公约组织成员国罗马尼亚领导人讨论了这一努力。罗马尼亚交通部长随后告诉记者，该国粮食出口能力将增加一倍，达到每月 400 万吨。</p><p>土耳其外交部没有回应就本周与美国会谈发表评论的请求</p><p>美国的计划将部分借鉴欧盟的一项倡议，即建立<a href="https://eu-solidarity-ukraine.ec.europa.eu/eu-assistance-ukraine/eu-ukraine-solidarity-lanes_en" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">被称为“团结通道”的</a>公路、铁路和海上航线，以尽可能顺利地将谷物和其他货物运进和运出乌克兰。</p><p>欧盟在战争爆发的头几个月制定了该计划，此前签署了道路运输协议，为运输商在乌克兰、摩尔多瓦和欧盟之间无需许可证的情况下过境铺平了道路。此后，欧盟投资了一系列基础设施项目，以建立更快的出口通道并加快海关程序。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1690" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/670c660e-e0c9-43e9-8c6d-a5cb03e5d9e4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>自2022年5月以来，这些航线已允许乌克兰出口4100万吨粮食，大大超过黑海粮食倡议所实现的目标。欧盟农业专员</p>贾努什·沃伊切霍夫斯基上个月表示，几个月内，欧盟的团结航线可能会取代乌克兰所有黑海谷物航线。<p></p><p>欧盟官员私下表示，他们相信，如果一切顺利的话，欧盟可以允许乌克兰平均每月出口500万至550万吨粮食。迄今为止，欧盟通道的最大成绩是11月份乌克兰谷物出口量为420万吨。 6月，乌克兰通过欧盟倡议出口了300万吨。欧盟官员表示，多瑙河航线占据了大部分出口，约占 60%。去年，黑海谷物倡议在鼎盛时期使乌克兰每月可以从敖德萨周围的三个港口出口约 600 万吨粮食。</p><p>然而，团结之路也遇到了困难。</p><p>欧盟官员表示，一些路线没有足够的人员和资源来迅速对入境货物进行必要的卫生和海关检查，有时会导致积压和延误，从而减缓交通并推高公路运输价格，从而推高乌克兰谷物的价格出口。乌克兰和罗马尼亚之间曾因乌克兰疏浚多瑙河三角洲运河以使运粮船只顺利通行而产生争议，现已解决。</p><p>美国官员表示，他们正在讨论提高多瑙河航线的效率，以允许更大的船只通过，为停泊空间腾出空间，并增加可用于通过重要运河运送船只的引航员数量。</p><p>然而，这些努力“不会取代黑海港口，首先是敖德萨，因此这不是解决方案；这确实是一个临时替代方案，”美国国际开发署欧洲和欧亚局助理局长艾琳·伊丽莎白·麦基（Erin Elizabeth McKee）在本月的一次简报中表示。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835919?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> TQ Samsun 号是黑海粮食倡议下最后一艘离开乌克兰的粮食船，于 7 月经过伊斯坦布尔。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：克里斯·麦格拉思/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>自粮食计划解体以来，多瑙河航线是乌克兰通过黑海出口粮食的唯一剩余途径，较小的船只经常将粮食运往罗马尼亚、保加利亚和其他地方的港口，然后运往世界市场。</p><p>俄罗斯威胁要切断多瑙河航线，本月早些时候袭击了伊兹梅尔河港，并于周日登上了一艘驶向该港口的土耳其船员船只。</p><p>俄罗斯国防部周二发布的一段事件视频显示，武装的俄罗斯士兵将一架直升机降落在该船的甲板上，并审问了船员。乌克兰外交部谴责这次拦截是“挑衅行为”。</p><p>俄罗斯威胁所有前往乌克兰的商船，军事分析人士称，俄罗斯此举是为了封锁进出乌克兰港口的民用船只。</p><p>乌克兰针对俄罗斯的袭击做出了回应， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-sea-drones-alter-balance-of-power-in-black-sea-391cebee?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">使用海上无人机</a>攻击俄罗斯军舰、一艘为莫斯科军队运送喷气燃料的油轮以及一座连接俄罗斯与被占领克里米亚半岛的桥梁。乌克兰还宣布黑海俄罗斯港口周围为“战争风险”地区，这表明俄罗斯自己的航道受到威胁。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="484" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835940?width=700&amp;height=484" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">本月初，俄罗斯无人机袭击摧毁了乌克兰伊兹梅尔河港的一座建筑。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：STRINGER/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Jared Malsin <a href="mailto:jared.malsin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(jared.malsin@wsj.com)</a>和 Laurence Norman ( <a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">laurence.norman@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 17:15:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-in-talks-to-develop-ukraine-grain-export-routes-3e597c3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-in-talks-to-develop-ukraine-grain-export-routes-3e597c3<author><![CDATA[Jared MalsinLaurence Norman]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>企业/工业出口</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>市场/营销</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>实物贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>工业出口</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>市场</category><category>营销</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>实物贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.K. Arrests Bulgarian Trio Suspected of Spying for Russia]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>此前，西方国家对冒充普通公民的俄罗斯人进行了一系列国际逮捕<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001136221"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835884?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">安全官员警告说，乌克兰战争加剧了俄罗斯间谍活动的威胁。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：彼得·尼科尔斯/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001136221"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-luhnow" itemprop="url" rel="author">大卫·卢诺</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/georgi-kantchev" itemprop="url" rel="author">格奥尔基·坎切夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 15 日中午 12:38（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-arrests-bulgarian-trio-suspected-of-spying-for-russia-1c7455f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伦敦——英国警方逮捕了五人，其中至少包括三名保加利亚国民，据信他们在为俄罗斯情报部门工作时在英国卧底，这是西方国家一系列逮捕冒充普通人的涉嫌<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/suspected-russian-agent-in-germany-had-access-to-western-intelligence-about-ukraine-war-11672255183?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯特工</a>的最新一起。 。</p><p>英国伦敦警察厅周二表示，三名男子和两名女子因涉嫌违反英国 1911 年《官方保密法》而被捕，该法将间谍活动定为刑事犯罪。大都会称，这五人已获保释，并将于 9 月出庭。</p><p>大都会称，五人中的三人——被大都会认定为 45 岁的奥林·罗塞夫 (Orlin Roussev)、42 岁的比塞尔·赞巴佐夫 (Biser Dzambazov) 和 31 岁的卡特琳·伊万诺娃 (Katrin Ivanova)——也被指控出于不正当目的持有虚假身份证件。</p><p>最先报道这起逮捕事件的英国广播公司 (BBC) 表示，这三人是保加利亚公民，据信为俄罗斯情报部门工作。据称，他们被发现持有来自英国、保加利亚、法国、意大利、西班牙、克罗地亚、斯洛文尼亚、希腊和捷克共和国的伪造护照和文件。</p><p>两名英国政府官员向《华尔街日报》证实了这一报道。</p><p>近几个月来，在多个国家发生了一系列类似的俄罗斯秘密间谍被捕事件， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-worries-it-has-become-a-haven-for-russian-spies-infiltrating-the-west-525021ba?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">这些间谍通常冒充南美人，</a>但生活在欧洲国家。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=5179E0B0-4C30-4FA3-B4FA-848FF823B8D9&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-k-arrests-bulgarian-trio-suspected-of-spying-for-russia-1c7455f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">英国间谍机构负责人邀请那些对乌克兰战争“默默感到震惊”的俄罗斯人与英国情报部门分享有关克里姆林宫的秘密。照片：马特·邓纳姆/美联社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>一名使用伪造的巴西身份的俄罗斯人在巴西被监禁，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-asks-brazil-to-hand-over-russian-accused-of-spying-ddd6a227" target="_blank" class="icon none">在美国面临间谍指控。荷兰</a>当局去年拦截了谢尔盖·切尔卡索夫，因为他据称试图以实习生身份渗透到国际刑事法院。据挪威官员称，另一名被指控的俄罗​​斯间谍在挪威担任大​​学研究员，也使用了假巴西身份。一对冒充阿根廷人的夫妇于四月在斯洛文尼亚被捕，并被指控为俄罗斯从事间谍活动。</p><p>另一对据称是俄罗斯间谍的夫妇——其中一人居住在巴西，另一人居住在希腊——在其他人被捕后不久于四月失踪。</p><p>北欧安全官员警告说，乌克兰战争加剧了俄罗斯间谍活动、 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-hackers-step-up-cyber-espionage-against-ukraine-and-allies-microsoft-says-aef4b31e" target="_blank" class="icon none">网络攻击和混合战争</a>的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/norway-to-expel-15-russian-diplomats-accused-of-espionage-aede77e2" target="_blank" class="icon none">威胁</a>。今年三月，波兰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/poland-says-russian-spies-sought-to-sabotage-western-arms-transfers-to-ukraine-d05361c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">指控六名外国公民</a>为俄罗斯从事间谍活动、准备破坏活动，以及试图破坏对乌克兰的军事和援助供应。</p><p>此次逮捕行动暴露了俄罗斯在世界各地广泛使用的“非法间谍”网络，除了经常驻扎在其大使馆的官方间谍之外。英国间谍头子、军情五处局长肯·麦卡勒姆去年表示，自乌克兰战争爆发以来，已有 400 多名在大使馆工作的俄罗斯疑似间谍被<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-spy-chief-says-russias-spy-network-in-europe-is-dented-following-expulsions-11668606799" target="_blank" class="icon none">驱逐出欧洲</a>，其中包括约 600 名俄罗斯官员。</p><p>就英国而言，三名间谍似乎不是俄罗斯人，而是保加利亚人。罗塞夫住在英格兰东海岸的度假小镇大雅茅斯，赞巴佐夫和伊万诺娃住在伦敦西北部郊区哈罗。</p><p>伦敦查塔姆研究所俄罗斯问题高级顾问研究员凯尔·吉尔斯表示，英国和整个西方国家有俄罗斯间谍或其他国家的人在为俄罗斯从事间谍活动，这并不令人意外。他说，尽管在这种情况下，目前还不清楚保加利亚人正在从事什么类型的情报工作，或者持续了多长时间。</p><p>贾尔斯说：“今天披露的逮捕行动与俄罗斯安插具有南美身份的特工的模式非常不同。”他补充说，保加利亚人可能一直在使用自己的身份。</p><p>罗塞夫的 LinkedIn 页面显示，过去十年他是一家名为 NextGen 的公司的所有者，该公司据称从事人工智能和信号情报业务，拦截私人通信等领域。他还曾在 2008-09 年度担任保加利亚能源部顾问。</p><p>根据他们的社交媒体资料，伊万诺娃和赞巴佐夫经营着“保加利亚社交平台”，这是一个为英国保加利亚人提供帮助的组织。该组织提供文件和其他建议以及免费英语课程方面的帮助。</p><p>伊万诺娃在 2019 年接受保加利亚国家广播电台采访时表示，她和她的伴侣赞巴佐夫于 2012 年搬到伦敦，并开始“从我们的客厅”帮助同胞。五年后，他们开始了社区组织。她说，他们都有全职“夜间工作”，但没有详细说明。她说她有很多“英国朋友”。</p><p>根据她的 LinkedIn 个人资料，伊万诺娃是一名医学实验室助理。根据赞巴佐夫<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a>页面上的帖子，他是一名狂热的足球迷。他的最后一篇文章是在 1 月 26 日。</p><p>保加利亚驻英国大使马林·雷科夫 (Marin Raykov) 告诉保加利亚国家通讯社 BTA，大使馆没有关于三名保加利亚人被拘留的任何细节，也没有得到英国当局的通知。雷科夫表示，根据英国惯例，当被拘留的外国人不希望本国得知其被拘留的情况时，英国当局不会通知大使馆。</p><p>近年来，由于俄罗斯特工在英国犯下的罪行，英国与俄罗斯的关系日益紧张。 2018年，俄罗斯特工在索尔兹伯里使用致命神经毒剂企图杀害<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-quiet-english-life-of-sergei-skripal-poisoned-former-russian-spy-1520797449?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">前俄罗斯双重间谍</a>谢尔盖·斯克里帕尔和他的女儿，两人均受重伤。 2006年，另一位前俄罗斯情报官员亚历山大·利特维年科在伦敦被谋杀。</p><p> 7月，英国政府通过了新立法，旨在削弱间谍活动和外国干预的威胁，包括英国选举的威胁。它首次将外国势力未公开的秘密特工定为刑事犯罪。此前的立法仅规定特工向外国势力移交敏感信息为非法行为，但并未将卧底间谍本身定为犯罪。新立法还将破坏英国民主的个人行为定为刑事犯罪，例如干预选举过程、网络攻击或代表外国势力发布虚假信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/8d8ed83e-2dd4-4860-bd54-92b7a7ea1ada.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>写信给 David Luhnow <a href="mailto:david.luhnow@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（david.luhnow@wsj.com）</a>和 Georgi Kantchev（ <a href="mailto:georgi.kantchev@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">georgi.kantchev@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 16:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-arrests-bulgarian-trio-suspected-of-spying-for-Russia-1c7455f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/uk-arrests-bulgarian-trio-suspected-of-spying-for-Russia-1c7455f<author><![CDATA[David LuhnowGeorgi Kantchev]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>间谍</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>间谍</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Turns to Well-Honed Playbook: Cut Rates, Hide Data]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>停止发布青年失业数据的举措引发了人们对中国经济衰退的不透明性的担忧<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135735"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="638" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835733?width=860&amp;height=638" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">随着今年夏天最新一​​批毕业生完成学业，经济学家原本预计青年失业率会更高。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Cfoto/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135735"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jason-douglas" itemprop="url" rel="author">杰森·道格拉斯</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">斯特拉·谢一帆</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 15 日上午 10:28 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-turns-to-well-honed-playbook-cut-rates-hide-data-bcfdd02"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>中国当局用一套精心设计的策略来应对又一个关于经济<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slashes-rates-suspends-youth-jobless-data-as-economy-signals-sharper-downturn-418301d6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的可怕消息</a>：他们降低了利率，并隐瞒了一些可能令人尴尬的经济数据。</p><p>投资者和经济学家表示，问题在于较低的借贷成本和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">更大的不透明度</a>并不是中国重振增长和恢复正在消失的经济信心所需要的。</p><p>中国经济正面临<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-slips-into-deflation-in-warning-sign-for-world-economy-bbefb179?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一系列挑战</a>，包括旷日持久的房地产紧缩、与以美国为首的西方国家关系恶化、以及在投资和出口等通常的增长引擎失灵的情况下难以培育消费拉动的经济扩张。</p><p>周二的数据显示，中国7月份的消费者支出、工业生产以及公共和私人投资指标大幅低于预期，加剧了经济方面的坏消息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835679?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>与此同时，中国国家统计局宣布将暂停公布中国青年失业率数据，称计划重新审视统计方法。</p><p>对于投资者和经济学家来说，突然的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-data-security-law-ships-ports-court-cases-universities-11638803230?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">停顿符合中国经济关键方面日益模糊的令人担忧的模式</a>。他们警告说，正当北京方面大肆宣扬<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-china-economy-capital-investment-3439d31a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">吸引外资的</a>重要性之际，北京<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-opaque-decision-making-confounds-business-governments-11673269970?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">方面压制信息流动的</a>举措可能会进一步打击本已脆弱的信心，并削弱中国作为投资目的地的吸引力。</p><p> “无论中国官员是否公布青年失业数据，都不会改变人们的看法，”北京精品投资银行 Chanson &amp; Co. 董事沉萌表示。 “隐瞒数据只会加剧市场对经济健康状况的担忧。”</p><p>近几个月来，中国当局加大了外国机构获取某些经济和金融数据的难度，包括公司注册信息、专利和某些统计数据。</p><p> 10月，中国国家统计局在季度国内生产总值数据即将发布前几个小时突然<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economic-data-gets-harder-to-find-as-growth-slows-11666092169?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">停止发布</a>，但没有提供任何解释。几天前，在中共<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/frosted-windows-swarming-police-signal-start-of-chinas-big-conclave-11665928844?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">十年两次代表大会</a>的背景下，中国根本没有发布月度官方贸易数据。它最终公布了这些数据，但除了引用了未具体说明的“工作安排”外， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-grew-3-9-in-the-third-quarter-11666576957?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">没有解释延迟的原因</a>。</p><p>资产管理公司 TCW Group 新兴市场董事总经理、前美国财政部官员戴维·洛文格 (David Loevinger) 表示，中国数据和政策制定透明度不断恶化，为投资世界第二大经济体“增加了另一层风险” 。</p><p> “我们都知道预测是困难的，尤其是对未来的预测，”他说。 “如果你不太确定现在发生了什么，那就更难了。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835741?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>中国还扩大了反间谍法，并<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-confirms-campaign-against-alleged-spying-by-foreign-consulting-companies-fef48e16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">突击搜查了包括贝恩公司在内的国际商业咨询公司的办公室</a>，与中国当局会面的外国企业高管表示，这是北京方面对其他公司<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-ratchets-up-pressure-on-foreign-companies-524b958e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">施加更大控制的</a>努力的一部分。世界观中国。</p><p>近几个月来，中国青年失业率的飙升成为国内外<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-youth-unemployment-xi-jobs-522028c5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">关注</a>的焦点。根据最新的官方数据，6月份中国16至24岁城市地区超过五分之一（21.3%）的人失业，这说明中国经济中的问题日益严重。截至 12 月，这一数字为 16.7%。</p><p>经济学家预计，随着今年夏天最新一​​批毕业生完成学业，青年失业率将再次上升，统计局预计将于周二公布数据。</p><p>但那从未发生过。 Instead, China&#39;s National Bureau of Statistics said it would hit pause on publishing the data while its statisticians looked at how the figures are compiled and whether students in particular should be counted among the unemployed if they are still studying while seeking work. The US and other countries count students as unemployed if they are actively seeking work and meet other standard criteria.</p><p> The headline measure of overall joblessness, the urban surveyed unemployment rate, moved higher for the first time since February, rising to 5.3% in July, from 5.2%.</p><p> Tuesday&#39;s batch of data revealed an economy struggling across the board. Figures last week showed consumer prices in China fell last month from a year earlier, while demand for loans from households and businesses evaporated.</p><p> On the international front, foreign direct investment in China in the second quarter touched its lowest level in decades and exports crumbled as Western consumers continued to pare back spending amid slowing growth and higher interest rates.</p><p> “The message is loud and clear: China is experiencing all-out deflation,” economists at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SCGLY" class="company-name">Société Générale</a> said in a note to clients after Tuesday&#39;s data release, ticking off a list of worsening indicators that included consumer and producer prices, exports, investment and consumption. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835743?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> So far, officials have struck a far more sanguine tone. On Tuesday, Fu Linghui, a spokesman for China&#39;s statistics bureau, said China hasn&#39;t seen deflation and won&#39;t see it in the future, repeating official rhetoric aimed at dispelling fears of a sustained decline in prices. China&#39;s main national evening news broadcast said the latest data showed the economy was on stable footing.</p><p> China&#39;s economy <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">expanded just 0.8%</a> in the second quarter compared with the first three months of the year, or a healthier-looking 6.3% when compared with the same quarter a year earlier, when Shanghai and other cities were hit by lockdowns. For many Chinese, though, growth <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-many-in-china-it-feels-like-a-recession-25ce4b68" target="_blank" class="icon none">feels much more anemic</a> than lackluster official figures suggest.</p><p> Some economists worry that without more forceful action to turn the economy around, China risks falling into a downward spiral of weakening growth as sagging business and household confidence reinforce declines in spending, hiring and investment.</p><p> On Tuesday, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BCS" class="company-name">Barclays</a> lowered its full-year GDP forecast to 4.5% from 4.9%, citing broad-based weakness in the economy and the absence of meaningful stimulus. The investment bank&#39;s new projection undershoots Chinese policy makers&#39; official GDP target of about 5% this year, a goal that many economists had regarded as conservative and unambitious.</p><p> An especially pressing task for policy makers is to salvage the property sector, which in recent years has accounted for as much as a fifth of China&#39;s total economic output. Home sales tumbled in June and July while one of China&#39;s biggest real-estate giants, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/HK/XHKG/2007" class="">Country Garden Holdings</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-property-company-country-garden-holdings-default-risk-22b3bd64?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">faces rising risk of debt default</a> .</p><p> China&#39;s central bank, the People&#39;s Bank of China, announced a flurry of interest rate cuts in response to the latest data, trimming lending rates on short- and medium-term loans for banks, steps that usually foreshadow cuts banks charge households and businesses to borrow.</p><p> Monetary easing probably won&#39;t be sufficient to arrest the slowdown in the economy, said Ting Lu, chief China economist at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NMR" class="company-name">Nomura</a> in Hong Kong. Lu and other economists say Beijing needs to consider bolder moves to revive flickering growth, such as propping up ailing real-estate developers and easing home-buying restrictions in major cities to stabilize the property market, or writing checks to consumers to drive spending.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Xiao Xiao and Grace Zhu in Beijing contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Jason Douglas at <a href="mailto:jason.douglas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jason.douglas@wsj.com</a> and Stella Yifan Xie at <a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stella.xie@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 14:28:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-turns-to-well-honed-playbook-cut-rates-hide-data-bcfdd02</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-turns-to-well-honed-playbook-cut-rates-hide-data-bcfdd02<author><![CDATA[Jason DouglasStella Yifan Xie]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济增长/衰退</category><category>就业/失业数据</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济增长</category><category>经济衰退</category><category>就业</category><category>失业数字</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Americans Flocked to Cancún for Vacation. Now They’re Thinking Twice.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The Mexican resort city saw a surge in 2021 and 2022, but tourist priorities have changed <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001121949"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="578" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832622?width=860&amp;height=578" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Travel companies that operate in the Cancún region are lowering prices in the short term.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Elizabeth Ruiz/AFP via Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001121949"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/allison-pohle" itemprop="url" rel="author">Allison Pohle</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 15, 2023 10:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cancun-mexico-travel-deals-safety-f5a49403"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> American travelers are having fun in the sun, but they&#39;re thinking beyond old standbys like Cancún.</p><p> US travelers put the brakes on trips to Cancún and neighboring Riviera Maya this spring, turning their attention to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-travelers-are-shunning-the-u-s-for-europe-5b5e08ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">destinations like Europe</a> , Japan and other parts of the Caribbean. The number of US travelers flying nonstop to Cancún—the biggest Mexican resort region—fell slightly compared with the same period a year before, according to <a href="https://www.trade.gov/data-visualization/apisi-92-monitor" target="_blank" class="icon none">data from</a> the US Department of Commerce&#39;s International Trade Administration. Hotels and airlines say they also have noticed occasional drops in demand.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “I&#39;m kind of Mexico-ed out,” says Khayla Morris, a 28-year-old content creator from Charlotte, NC Morris traveled to Cancún with her sisters in May 2022, and went in 2017 and 2018.</p><p> Travel companies that operate in the Cancún region are lowering prices in the short term, and airfare has also dropped compared with last year as air carriers have bet on the long term and increased routes.</p><h3> Looking elsewhere</h3><p> Executives from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SAVE" class="company-name">Spirit Airlines</a> and Playa Hotels and Resorts said in recent earnings calls that demand for Cancún and the surrounding region has fluctuated in recent months.</p><p> Ryan Hymel, Playa&#39;s chief financial officer, said during the company&#39;s earnings call this is due to “destination fatigue.” Mexico was the place to be in 2021 and 2022, but became less of a priority as people could travel to Europe or other Caribbean spots, he said on the call. Playa CEO Bruce Wardinski said travelers have many options in the high season.</p><p> US travelers still love Mexico. The tourism board for Quintana Roo, the Mexican state that is home to Cancún and the Riviera Maya, says US visitor numbers for the region were up about 12% from January to June, compared with the first six months of 2019. That means the spring figures represent a slowdown in pandemic-era growth, not a decrease in the US visitor market, the tourism board says. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="527" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-832869?width=700&amp;height=527" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> More police officers have been patrolling Cancún in recent months.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: PAOLA CHIOMANTE/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> US nonstop passenger numbers to Cancún picked back up in June and July, exceeding those from the year prior, International Trade Administration data shows.</p><p> Many US tourists <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-mexico-vacation-during-the-pandemic-the-rewards-vs-risks-11610655230?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">chose Mexico</a> early in the pandemic. Unlike other major destinations, the country didn&#39;t require proof of vaccination or a negative Covid test to enter.</p><p> Mexico&#39;s tourism business council has cited a few reasons for the drop in US visitors this spring, including the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mexicos-peso-surges-to-strongest-level-since-2015-4286806?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">appreciation of the Mexican peso</a> to its strongest level in nearly eight years, which makes Mexico more expensive for international tourists. Other factors include more competition from other destinations and traveler concerns about security.</p><p> Drug-related violence caused the homicide rate in parts of Mexico to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cancun-tulum-riviera-maya-mexico-drugs-homicides-11648853578?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reach record levels</a> in recent years. More police officers have begun patrolling Cancún in recent months.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you vacation in Cancún?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Vacationers feel more anxious about traveling to Cancún due to reports of violence, but many ultimately end up traveling there anyway because they stay in the tourist-centric hotel zone and Riviera Maya, says Christine Hardenberger, owner of Modern Travel Professionals, a travel agency based in Fredericksburg, Va. They find their money goes much further compared with other international destinations, especially at all-inclusive resorts.</p><h3> Expect bargains</h3><p> Travelers should expect deals this fall as hotels compete for their business, says Tulio Baruch, director of sales marketing for the upscale Viceroy Riviera Maya.</p><p> The biggest spenders tend to be less price-sensitive. In the Cancún Riviera Maya market, five-star hotels outperformed four-star hotels by 10 percentage points, Hyatt CEO Mark Hoplamazian said. He cited data from Hyatt-owned ALG Vacations, a vacation package company that includes brands such as CheapCaribbean.com and Southwest Vacations.</p><p> But visitor numbers dropped at some five-star resorts. US travelers booked 15% fewer rooms at the Viceroy Riviera Maya last quarter, compared with a year earlier, Baruch says. Vacationers opted instead for Italy, Greece and Japan, he says.</p><p> Baruch says a number of new luxury resorts have opened in the area in recent years. The combination of declining demand and more supply meant hotels had to lower rates, he says. Last quarter, US travelers to his resort paid about $626 a night, $45 cheaper than a year prior, he said.</p><p> The average round-trip economy flight to Cancún this month costs $424, a 10% decrease from last year, according to data from travel search-engine Kayak.</p><p> Spirit&#39;s flights to Cancún were sold out in April, even at higher prices, says Matt Klein, the airline&#39;s executive vice president and chief commercial officer. But in June, revenue fell in the “very high double-digit numbers” compared with the year before, he said in the company&#39;s earnings call. “The demand just fell off,” he said. Spirit lowered fares to address the drop-off.</p><p> Many travel executives think the drop in demand is temporary and are betting on long-term interest by adding flight capacity. United Airlines recently said it would fly its larger, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BA" class="company-name">Boeing</a> 777-200s on three routes to Cancún starting in late October.</p><p> Morris, the Charlotte content creator, says she is watching her money more closely because of inflation. She plans to head back to Cancún this spring for a wedding, but will give priority to other beach destinations, such as Turks and Caicos.</p><p> “If I&#39;m gonna spend this kind of money, I&#39;m gonna go somewhere I really want to go,” she says.</p><p> <em>Sign up for the new</em> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/newsletters?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none"><em>WSJ Travel newsletter</em></a> <em>for more tips and insights from the Journal&#39;s travel team.</em></p><p class="articleTagLine"> — <em>Anthony Harrup</em> contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Allison Pohle at <a href="mailto:allison.pohle@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">allison.pohle@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 14:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cancun-mexico-travel-deals-safety-f5a49403</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/cancun-mexico-travel-deals-safety-f5a49403<author><![CDATA[Allison Pohle]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>住宿/餐厅/酒吧</category><category>Lodgings</category><category> Hotels/Motels</category><category> Trusts/Funds/Financial Vehicles</category><category>私人产权</category><category>Alternative Investments</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>Tourism</category><category> Venture Capital</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Consumer Deals</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>个人财务</category><category>Consumer Spending/Budgeting</category><category> Travel Deals/Packages</category><category> Travel</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Playa Hotels &amp; Resorts NV</category><category> PLYA</category><category> Hyatt Hotels</category><category> H</category><category> Spirit Airlines</category><category> SAVE</category><category> Ryan Hymel</category><category> Bruce Wardinski</category><category> Mark Hoplamazian</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>consumer deals</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>个人财务</category><category>consumer spending</category><category> budgeting</category><category> travel deals</category><category> packages</category><category> travel</category><category>住宿</category><category>餐馆</category><category>酒吧</category><category>hotels</category><category> motels</category><category> trusts</category><category>资金</category><category>financial vehicles</category><category> private equity</category><category> alternative investments</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>闲暇</category><category>艺术</category><category>款待</category><category>tourism</category><category> venture capital </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Brutal Heat Tests Ability of Energy Exporters to Keep Their Citizens Cool]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Soaring demand for electricity is overwhelming aging power networks throughout the Middle East <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135592"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="607" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834890?width=860&amp;height=607" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Power outages in Cairo have prompted concerns that the city&#39;s domestic gas supply is running low.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: AMR ABDALLAH DALSH/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135592"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chao-deng" itemprop="url" rel="author">Chao Deng</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 15, 2023 7:48 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brutal-summer-heat-tests-ability-of-energy-exporters-to-keep-their-citizens-cool-6cc07445"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> CAIRO—Energy-rich countries across the Middle East and North Africa are struggling to keep power flowing to their own citizens during intense summer heat, with Egypt the latest to impose rolling blackouts.</p><p> The outages here have prompted concerns that Cairo&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/egypt-dims-the-lights-in-cairo-to-free-up-more-gas-for-europe-11668681057?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">domestic gas supply</a> is running low.</p><p> Iran and Iraq, both oil exporters, are also facing blackouts as blistering temperatures envelop the region, with the thermometer reaching 122 degrees Fahrenheit in Baghdad <strong>,</strong> buckling aging power grids.</p><p> A lack of electricity to run air conditioners, fridges and fans led to small protests on the streets of Baghdad this month. Similarly, in some cities in Iran, where electricity usage hit a record last month, the weight of demand has caused power networks to collapse in recent weeks.</p><p> The Iranian government shut banks and public offices for two days to discourage residents <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-begins-two-day-shutdown-as-heat-wave-worsens-e756dcfc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">from going outside in the heat</a> , and officials have urged people to consume less electricity.</p><p> In Egypt, analysts say that extreme summer temperatures have been exacerbated by a lack of maintenance of some power stations, rising demand from a fast-growing population and falling output at the country&#39;s largest gas field.</p><p> “It&#39;s very likely that Egypt has a shortage in gas,” said Timothy Kaldas, deputy director of the Tahrir Institute for Middle East Policy, a Washington-based nonprofit. “Production is down and there are no exports at a time when they&#39;re desperate to export.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="502" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835729?width=700&amp;height=502" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Egyptian President Abdel Fattah Al Sisi, center, and other officials looking at mockups of natural-gas facilities in 2018.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: handout/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Egyptian government denies it is facing a gas shortage and says power cuts are necessary because of rocketing demand during the heat wave. Blackouts this summer have been especially painful. Temperatures topped 114 degrees Fahrenheit in late July, according to the Egyptian Meteorological Authority.</p><p> Still, the country&#39;s gas exports, which peaked in December, according to commodities data firm Kpler, fell to zero in June and rose only slightly in July.</p><p> Problems with power and gas supplies were among the grievances that contributed to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323899704578583191518313964?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the downfall</a> of President Mohammed Morsi in 2013. Electricity outages persisted after President Abdel Fattah Al Sisi came to power, leading him to spend enormous sums to increase the capacity of the country&#39;s power network. The 2015 discovery of a mammoth gas field in the Mediterranean, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bp-to-buy-10-stake-in-enis-giant-zohr-gas-field-off-egypt-coast-1480095283?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">known as Zohr</a> , allowed Egypt at one point to increase gas production and decrease imports.</p><p> But pressure by the government to accelerate the development of Zohr caused water infiltration problems that have persisted and which are in part responsible for lower gas output this year, according to Egyptian officials familiar with the matter.<br><br> In a <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m2_bBeTujfY" target="_blank" class="icon none">speech</a> in October, Sisi said that he had told <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/E" class="company-name">Eni</a> —one of the developers of the Zohr gas field—it had 18 months to develop the reservoir, compared with the five-year timeline the Italian firm had proposed. <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>What further consequences could arise from a gas shortage in Egypt?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Egyptian gas output will likely fall to a <a href="https://www.fitchsolutions.com/oil-gas/declining-gas-production-egypt-underlines-need-further-discoveries-18-07-2023?fSWebArticleValidation=true&amp;mkt_tok=NzMyLUNLSC03NjcAAAGNewGSpgjRphyEmHgXsKqcU1Hw3j8KQZmQh6MbqJXYB2SdmamMwOR0gaEP-3ipAytil2KuktxcI45KahM09IkuYum0Z9niAvi0GIeSVoVngg" target="_blank" class="icon none">new three-year low</a> of 64.9 billion cubic meters this year, according to BMI, a subsidiary of credit-ratings firm Fitch, amid “ongoing water infiltration issues” at Zohr. The field has produced about 40% of the country&#39;s total gas output in recent years.</p><p> Eni and the Egyptian government say it isn&#39;t true that technical problems at Zohr have caused a decline in production capacity.</p><p> “A number of projects [are] now running to improve the processing capacity and…to ultimately sustain the production,” a spokesman for the Oil Ministry said about Zohr.</p><p> Cairo is now exploring whether Israel can pipe more natural gas to Egypt, according to some of the officials.</p><p> Israel <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-signs-gas-deal-with-israel-egypt-in-bid-to-wean-itself-off-russian-supplies-11655299886?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">agreed last year</a> to step up gas exports to Egypt for the purpose of liquefying it for re-export to Europe. But when Israeli Energy Minister</p> Israel Katz said this month that his country would increase its own exports, he said that Egypt was facing “a serious crisis” and needed more gas for local consumption.<p></p><p> In poorer parts of Egypt, including in the south, households say electricity cuts are lasting for hours and some complain of lack of water because their water pumps also rely on electricity. Other Egyptians say that outages aren&#39;t equally dispersed and don&#39;t affect wealthy coastal towns of the north including Alamein, where Sisi and the country&#39;s elite are known to spend the summers.</p><p> The prime minister&#39;s office said in a statement on Facebook last month that authorities&#39; power-saving plan excluded three coastal governorates, including where Alamein is located, because of what it said were low consumption rates there.</p><p> In the northern city of Port Said, Dina Tal&#39;at blamed the heat during power outages for her 5-year-old son&#39;s vomiting. The family lost electricity for more than two days, leaving much of the food in their fridge to rot as temperatures became unbearable. When the power did come back on, it was only for three hours.<br><br> “I have never ever seen such a disregard for the average citizen,” Tal&#39;at said of the government.</p><p> Mina Rafaat, a teacher living on the outskirts of Cairo, said her elderly mother fainted after the electricity in their home went off for five hours, leaving them without air conditioning.</p><p> “It&#39;s really tough,” she said. “I&#39;m afraid that this will happen to her again since this crisis seems to be persisting.”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Summer Said, Menna Farouk and Ahmed Medhat contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Chao Deng at <a href="mailto:chao.deng@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chao.deng@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 11:48:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brutal-summer-heat-tests-ability-of-energy-exporters-to-keep-their-citizens-cool-6cc07445</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brutal-summer-heat-tests-ability-of-energy-exporters-to-keep-their-citizens-cool-6cc07445<author><![CDATA[Chao Deng]]></author><category> Energy</category><category> Oil and Gas Upstream Operations</category><category> Natural Gas Extraction</category><category> Oil and Natural Gas Exploration</category><category> Fossil Fuels</category><category> Natural Gas</category><category> Oil and Gas</category><category> Blackouts</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Disasters/Accidents</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> blackouts</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>disasters</category><category> accidents</category><category> energy</category><category> oil and gas upstream operations</category><category> natural gas extraction</category><category> oil and natural gas exploration</category><category> fossil fuels</category><category> natural gas</category><category> oil and gas </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Launches Emergency Rate Rise to Stem Economic Turmoil]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>卢布最近的下滑反映出俄罗斯应对通胀、制裁和劳动力短缺的不确定性不断增加<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135495"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835219?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Elvira Nabiullina, chair of Russia&#39;s central bank, which raised rates by 3.5 percentage points on Tuesday.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Alexander Kulebyakin/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001135495"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/georgi-kantchev" itemprop="url" rel="author">格奥尔基·坎切夫</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/chelsey-dulaney" itemprop="url" rel="author">切尔西·杜兰尼</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated Aug. 15, 2023 6:38 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-imposes-emergency-interest-rate-rise-to-halt-ruble-selloff-f3668bd1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>俄罗斯央行在一次紧急会议上上调了关键利率，以遏制<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-ruble-at-weakest-level-since-early-days-of-ukraine-war-eaef275f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">卢布大幅抛售</a>和通胀回升，以应对莫斯科乌克兰战争造成的不断上升的金融成本。</p><p> The bank on Tuesday raised the rate to 12% from 8.5%, a day after the currency temporarily fell past 100 to the US dollar for the first time since the weeks after Russia invaded Ukraine.由于预期这一决定，卢布有所回升，但今年仍下跌近四分之一，使其成为全球表现最差的货币之一。</p><p>尽管去年陷入衰退，但俄罗斯经济能够<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-attacked-russias-economy-the-result-is-another-stalemate-99ec913b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">经受住西方制裁浪潮，</a>这要归功于石油和天然气收入的暴利、政府的大力刺激以及该国迅速将<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-defies-sanctions-by-selling-oil-above-price-cap-bae1c271?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">贸易从欧洲转移到亚洲的</a>能力。</p><p>但卢布最近的下跌表明经济相对稳定的时期已经过去。俄罗斯陷入了快速上升的通货膨胀和政府需要借贷和支出来维持乌克兰战争的困境之间，这对经济来说是一个有毒的组合。它还面临制裁日益严重的影响和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-big-economic-problem-not-enough-workers-d5164d47?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">严重的劳动力短缺</a>。</p><p>凯投宏观(Capital Economics)高级新兴市场经济学家利亚姆·皮奇(Liam Peach)表示，俄罗斯的宏观经济稳定性“现在比战争初期以来的任何时候都更加脆弱”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835687?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>今年进口快速增长、出口放缓，加上六月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wagner-prigozhin-putin-mutiny-moscow-march-7072d6e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">瓦格纳叛变流产</a>后的资本外流和政治不确定性，都导致卢布在最近几周走低。</p><p>分析人士表示，卢布的贬值表明人们越来越认识到：战争和俄罗斯的孤立将持续数年。在这种情况下，俄罗斯的经济将长期受到军事足迹扩大和西方制裁的抑制。</p><p> “卢布下跌反映了战争导致的俄罗斯经济根本失衡，”前俄罗斯央行官员、现任柏林卡内基俄罗斯欧亚中心非常驻学者亚历山德拉·普罗科彭科(Alexandra Prokopenko)表示。 “从根本上来说，央行利率无法改变趋势。”</p><p>对于俄罗斯经济来说，更长的战争意味着更高的通货膨胀，因为政府在武器和社会措施上花费更多，以安抚国内民众。卢布疲软使得进口产品更加昂贵。</p><p>长期制裁意味着俄罗斯的国际供应链将继续受到干扰，进一步加大价格压力。目前，俄罗斯能够进口许多西方禁止的商品——从iPhone到汽车再到电脑芯片——但它是通过第三国进口的，这种迂回方式会提高价格。</p><p>央行表示：“通胀压力正在加大。” “卢布贬值对物价的传导势头正在增强，通胀预期也在上升。”</p><p>继<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-raises-rates-as-ukraine-war-costs-mount-a41bfa23?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">7 月份加息幅度</a>超出预期之后，央行周二采取了这一举措。该银行的下一次会议计划于九月举行。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>俄罗斯经济下一步将何去何从？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>对于克里姆林宫来说，经济恶化带来了一系列新的挑战，因为其军队在战场上对抗乌克兰的进步。长期战争的输赢往往取决于各国维持和投射经济实力的能力。西方国家已花费数十亿美元来支撑乌克兰的经济并为其战争提供物资。</p><p>央行将卢布贬值归因于该国贸易状况恶化。莫斯科以低于全球价格的价格出售原油，并已停止向传统上最大的市场欧洲大部分地区供应天然气。</p><p>俄罗斯央行上周数据显示，今年前七个月俄罗斯经常项目盈余（衡量流入经济的资金的广义指标）缩减至252亿美元，与去年同期相比下降了85%。</p><p>俄罗斯贸易地位的削弱部分源于对中国和土耳其等国进口依赖的增加。在俄罗斯的战时经济中，国内需求超过了俄罗斯的生产能力，特别是在因西方企业撤出和制裁而受到打击的行业。 2023年前7个月俄罗斯商品进口同比增长18%。</p><p>随着战争的拖延，政治动荡也将继续削弱卢布的汇率。瓦格纳叛变给俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京(Vladimir Putin</a> )带来了不确定性，自今年年初以来，该货币的缓慢下跌步伐加快了。</p>掌握权力。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835689?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>人民币汇率的波动也为了解政府与央行之间在如何管理经济方面的紧张关系提供了一个难得的窗口。克里姆林宫的一名高级助手周一将卢布疲软归咎于宽松的货币政策。</p><p>一些人认为，公众的相互指责表明，自六月下旬瓦格纳雇佣兵组织领导人叶夫根尼·普里戈任领导的兵变失败以来，俄罗斯政界内部的紧张局势继续加剧。</p><p> BlueBay 资产管理公司高级新兴市场策略师蒂莫西·阿什 (Timothy Ash) 表示：“这可能是精英斗争的延伸，就像普里戈任和瓦格纳之间的斗争一样，针对政府中的经济技术官僚。” “这普遍表明高层领导层缺乏信心。”</p><p>信心丧失是卢布价值面临的主要风险。瓦格纳叛变后的几天里，俄罗斯人从俄罗斯银行提取了大约 10 亿美元，由于他们选择现金并将资金藏匿海外，导致自战争开始以来资金持续外流。分析师称，卢布贬值、通胀上升和政治分歧加剧都可能鼓励更多资本外逃，进而加剧卢布压力。</p><p>克里姆林宫稳定卢布汇率的另一个选择是：重新实施资本管制以支撑卢布需求。在卢布于 2022 年战争爆发后几个月暴跌后，这种大幅提高利率和限制资金流出的方案有助于稳定卢布。</p><p>凯投宏观的皮奇表示：“短期内，他们可以通过这样的大幅加息来减缓出血速度，但这并不会从根本上改变卢布的走势。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1DFAFAD1-8AAF-44B7-B265-599DD90D1C97&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Frussia-imposes-emergency-interest-rate-rise-to-halt-ruble-selloff-f3668bd1&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> As the West scrambles to move away from Russian energy sources and imposes sanctions on Moscow, China and India have stepped in to fill the gap. WSJ examines how those countries have boosted Russia&#39;s revenue from oil sales, supporting its economy. Photo illustration: Sharon Shi<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>较高的利率将使当地储户更愿意将钱存入卢布，但也会推高借贷和投资成本，从而给俄罗斯本已疲软的经济增长带来压力。</p><p>还有另一个复杂因素：这也将使俄罗斯政府偿还国内债务的成本更高。过去一年，政府大肆举债，以弥补石油折扣销售收入的缺口。其中大部分债务以地方政府债券的形式发行，并以浮动利率发行。</p><p>虽然俄罗斯 7 月份总体通胀率看似温和，同比增长 4.3%，但较 5 月份 2.5% 大幅上升。去年入侵后冲击造成的高比较基数掩盖了价格上涨的大部分内容。央行周二表示，按季节性调整后的年化计算，过去三个月的通胀率平均为 7.6%。</p><p>央行周一表示，货币贬值推高了依赖进口的家电、汽车和水果等商品的价格。在定于三月份举行的总统选举之前，物价上涨是政府的另一个担忧。</p><p>写信给Georgi Kantchev <a href="mailto:georgi.kantchev@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（georgi.kantchev@wsj.com）</a>和Chelsey Dulaney（ <a href="mailto:chelsey.dulaney@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">chelsey.dulaney@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 10:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-imposes-emergency-interest-rate-rise-to-halt-ruble-selloff-f3668bd1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-imposes-emergency-interest-rate-rise-to-halt-ruble-selloff-f3668bd1<author><![CDATA[Georgi KantchevChelsey Dulaney]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字/价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>贸易壁垒/限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>通货膨胀数字</category><category>价格指数</category><category>货币政策</category><category>利率</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>政治</category><category>贸易壁垒</category><category>限制</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Donald Trump Indicted in Georgia Over Effort to Overturn Election Results]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Charges brought by Fulton County&#39;s district attorney mark fourth criminal case against former president <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831598/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="2024 年共和党总统提名的领跑者、前总统唐纳德·特朗普否认有不当行为。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Former President Donald Trump, the front-runner for the 2024 Republican presidential nomination, denies wrongdoing. Melissa Sue Gerrits/Getty Images <span>Melissa Sue Gerrits/Getty Images</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116987"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116987"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/cameron-mcwhirter" itemprop="url" rel="author">Cameron McWhirter</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jan-wolfe" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jan Wolfe</a></span> , <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/aruna-viswanatha" itemprop="url" rel="author">Aruna Viswanatha</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sadie-gurman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sadie Gurman</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 15, 2023 1:22 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> ATLANTA—A grand jury here charged <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> , Rudy Giuliani and other Trump allies with operating a criminal enterprise that sought to overturn <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/joe-biden">Joe Biden</a> &#39;s electoral victory in Georgia, marking the fourth time the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-guide-to-donald-trumps-legal-perils-b9b64891?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">former president has been indicted</a> this year and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-charges-facing-donald-trump-and-how-he-might-defend-himself-53a2b45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">deepening his legal woes</a> ahead of the 2024 election.</p><p> There were 19 people in total <a href="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/documents/GATRUMPINDICTMENT081423.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">charged in the indictment</a> , including former Trump White House chief of staff Mark Meadows and legal adviser Sidney Powell.</p><p> Taken together, the Georgia charges allege a sweeping criminal conspiracy to overturn the 2020 election result and undermine US democracy. They describe calls, emails, and other efforts to allegedly press state and federal officials into backing the effort to find votes Trump lacked to win or assert that he was victorious both in Georgia and other states he lost.</p><p> The sprawling indictment, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fani-willis-the-no-nonsense-georgia-prosecutor-on-a-collision-course-with-donald-trump-600b88f8?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">brought by</a> Fulton County District Attorney Fani Willis, covers some of the same ground as the federal case Trump faces in Washington, but goes into greater detail on the effort in Georgia and offers some new elements of the alleged conspiracy. It charges Trump with 13 felonies, alleging he pushed false claims of voter fraud in Georgia and pressured Republican officials to help him secure the state&#39;s Electoral College votes. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=63AF554A-ED80-41F6-BE4D-ADF5F7ECFA84&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Former president Donald Trump is facing four separate indictments at both state and federal levels. WSJ breaks down each of the indictments and what they mean for his 2024 presidential campaign. Photo Illustration: Annie Zhao<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Willis, whose investigation lasted more than two years, used the state&#39;s sweeping antiracketeering law to describe an elaborate plot to stay in power over the will of Georgia voters. Biden narrowly won the state in 2020.</p><p> “The defendants engaged in a criminal racketeering enterprise to overturn Georgia&#39;s presidential election results,” Willis said during a press conference late Monday, adding that the defendants pursued an illegal goal of allowing Trump to seize a presidential term.</p><p> She said she would seek a trial date in the next six months. She gave the defendants until Friday, Aug. 25, to turn themselves in.</p><p> Trump, on his Truth Social platform, declared the investigation a witch hunt. “他们为什么不在 2.5 年前起诉？ Because they wanted to do it right in the middle of my political campaign,” he said.</p><p> Trump&#39;s lawyers issued a statement that said in part, “We look forward to a detailed review of this indictment which is undoubtedly just as flawed and unconstitutional as this entire process has been.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="896" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/a7dc45f6-d690-4f27-9034-c24e2929ee1d-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> The indictment details 161 separate acts it says were undertaken as part of the conspiracy to reverse the election outcome, beginning with a speech Trump gave declaring victory the day after the presidential election. It also alleges that the criminal enterprise operated in Georgia outside of Fulton County as well as in other states, including Michigan, Arizona, Pennsylvania, Nevada and New Mexico.</p><p> The indictment alleges Giuliani led the effort in battleground states, including Georgia, to keep Trump in power. Giuliani called the indictment “an affront to American Democracy” and said it does “permanent, irrevocable harm to our justice system.”</p><p> Several individuals are charged with breaching voting machines in Coffee County, a rural county about 200 miles from Atlanta. Those defendants, including Powell, were charged with conspiracy to commit computer theft. Powell had pushed false claims that voting machines had been hacked to flip votes from Trump to Biden.</p><p> Willis also indicted John Eastman and Kenneth Chesebro, who argued in legal memos that then-Vice President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mike-pence">Mike Pence</a> could block Electoral College votes from being certified.</p><p> Other defendants include Jenna Ellis, a former Trump lawyer, and</p> Jeffrey Clark, a Trump administration Justice Department official who urged his colleagues to launch investigations in Georgia based on Trump&#39;s unsupported claims of voting fraud. A lawyer for Ellis didn&#39;t immediately return calls for comment.<p></p><p> “ Jeff Clark was simply doing his job in 2020 and he doesn&#39;t deserve to be subjected to this naked political lawfare, especially not by a publicity hound like Willis,” said Rachel Cauley, a spokeswoman for Center for Renewing America, the conservative think tank where Clark works. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=1F164012-9314-4C51-AF75-113013B9D8A3&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdonald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Fulton County District Attorney Fani Willis announced 41 counts against former President Donald Trump and 18 other people for operating a criminal enterprise that sought to overturn the 2020 election in Georgia. Photo: John Bazemore/Associated Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Lawyers for Eastman, Meadows, Chesebro and Powell didn&#39;t immediately respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Three other defendants charged were “fake electors” or “alternate electors,” individuals who signed a certificate falsely stating that Trump had won Georgia in the 2020 election and declared themselves the state&#39;s “duly elected and qualified” electors.</p><p> Elsewhere, political reaction split along usual partisan lines.</p><p> House Speaker Kevin McCarthy (R., Calif.) in a tweet late Monday accused Willis of attacking Trump to advance her own political career.</p><p> Rep. Elise Stefanik of New York, a member of House GOP leadership, said: “President Trump had every legal right to challenge the results of the election” and accused Willis of bias.</p><p> Rep. Nikema Williams (D., Ga.), who also serves as chair of Georgia Democrats, said Trump had assaulted democracy by trying to disenfranchise Georgia voters because he didn&#39;t like the result of the 2020 election. “Now, Donald Trump is facing the consequences of his actions,” Williams said.</p><p> The indictment also charged several of the defendants with filing false documents, in some cases by sending the false elector certificates, and, in the case of Trump and Eastman, by filing a New Year&#39;s Eve lawsuit in federal court that included alleged lies such as that thousands of minors and dead people voted in the 2020 election.</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> In addition to the 19 defendants, the indictment describes a further 30 people as unindicted co-conspirators, leaving open the possibility of additional charges in connection with the case.</p><p> The move by Willis, a Democrat, had been widely anticipated. In April, she said she planned to announce charging decisions this summer, and she had told local law-enforcement leaders to prepare for the “significant public reaction” her announcement could trigger.</p><p> Willis opened the probe on the basis of a recorded Jan. 2, 2021, phone call in which then-President Trump urged Republican Brad Raffensperger, Georgia&#39;s top elections official, to find enough votes to overturn the election. Trump, the front-runner for the 2024 Republican presidential nomination, denies wrongdoing and has said the call was perfect.</p><p> Willis convened a special grand jury, which heard from more than 75 witnesses, wrote a report summarizing its findings and recommended criminal charges against several people whose identities haven&#39;t been made public. The special grand jury lacked the authority to issue indictments, however, prompting Willis to present evidence to a regular grand jury.</p><p> In November 2020, Trump lost the election in Georgia to Biden by roughly 12,000 votes out of five million cast. Trump and his supporters claimed the election was stolen, but statewide recounts and a partial forensic audit overseen by state election officials found no evidence of widespread fraud. Court challenges failed. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831333?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The indictment brought by Fulton County District Attorney Fani Willis alleges the former president pushed false claims of voter fraud and pressured Republican officials to help him secure Georgia&#39;s Electoral College votes.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Brynn Anderson/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Monday indictment also outlines multiple episodes involving Meadows, who was the White House chief of staff when Trump tried to overturn the 2020 election result. Meadows featured minimally in the federal election-interference case and wasn&#39;t identifiable as one of the six unindicted co-conspirators in that case, where Trump is the only defendant.</p><p> The new indictment levels two charges against Meadows related to the alleged conspiracy, saying he attended meetings where Trump allegedly brought up lies about election fraud and he worked to arrange Trump calls with state officials to further the efforts, including the call during which Trump asked Georgia officials to find him more votes.</p><p> The indictment also describes a meeting at which Trump and Meadows allegedly asked Trump aide John McEntee to prepare a memo on how to disrupt or delay Congress&#39;s Jan. 6 counting of the electoral votes. And it charges both Trump and Meadows with trying to get Raffensperger to violate his oath of public office by pressuring him to change the results there.</p><p> Earlier this year, Trump was indicted by Manhattan District Attorney Alvin Bragg over the payment of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/grand-jury-votes-to-indict-donald-trump-a9512240?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hush money to a porn star</a> on the eve of the 2016 election, marking the first time a former president has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/donald-trump-indictment-arrest-da-bragg?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">faced criminal charges</a> .</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How will the latest charges against Donald Trump play out?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Then in June, federal prosecutors led by special counsel Jack Smith unsealed <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-federal-case-against-trump-on-the-mar-a-lago-documents-12054f5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a sweeping indictment</a> alleging the former president <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-in-document-case-b4e563d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">held on to classified documents</a> he knew he shouldn&#39;t have retained access to, shared them with others and directed his staff to help him evade authorities&#39; efforts to get them back. The case is being handled in Florida.</p><p> A superseding federal indictment returned in late July charged Trump with three additional counts, including one of willful <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-lawyers-jack-smith-jan-6-58c2fd14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">retention of national-defense information</a> , stemming from a classified national-security document prosecutors said he showed to visitors at his golf club in New Jersey.</p><p> Trump was indicted a third time Aug. 1 in a further criminal case accusing him of trying to subvert the will of American voters through his attempts to cling to power after he lost the 2020 election. <a href="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/documents/trumpindictment080123.pdf" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">That indictment</a> , by a federal grand jury in Washington, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-new-charges-facing-donald-trump-and-how-he-might-defend-himself-53a2b45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">charges Trump with four crimes</a> , including conspiring to defraud the US, obstructing an official proceeding and conspiring against the rights of voters by his actions that culminated in the Jan. 6, 2021, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-protesters-are-in-the-building-inside-the-capitol-stormed-by-a-pro-trump-mob-11609984654?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">attack by his supporters</a> on the US Capitol.</p><p> Trump pleaded not guilty in the New York, Florida and Washington, DC, cases. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/537f22eb-7442-4360-8305-39f89aae3339.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —Byron Tau, Alex Leary, Lindsay Wise and Isaac Yu contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Cameron McWhirter at <a href="mailto:Cameron.McWhirter@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Cameron.McWhirter@wsj.com</a> , Jan Wolfe at <a href="mailto:jan.wolfe@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">jan.wolfe@wsj.com</a> , Aruna Viswanatha at <a href="mailto:aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">aruna.viswanatha@wsj.com</a> and Sadie Gurman at <a href="mailto:sadie.gurman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sadie.gurman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 05:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/donald-trump-indicted-georgia-election-interference-case-64deb461<author><![CDATA[Cameron McWhirterJan WolfeAruna ViswanathaSadie Gurman]]></author><category> trump legal</category><category>华尔街日报-美国新闻</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>Trump Legal</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Wall Street Is Ready to Scoop Up Commercial Real Estate on the Cheap]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Firms are raising billions of dollars for funds to target assets with slumping values <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-833597/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="Vacancy rates in the office market have soared amid a sluggish return-to-the-office pace." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Vacancy rates in the office market have soared amid a sluggish return-to-the-office pace. BRENDAN MCDERMID/REUTERS <span>BRENDAN MCDERMID/REUTERS</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133014"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001133014"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/peter-grant" itemprop="url" rel="author">Peter Grant</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 15, 2023 12:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Wall Street firms are raising new funds to acquire <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-return-to-the-office-has-stalled-e0af9741?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">office buildings</a> , apartments and other troubled commercial real estate, looking to scoop up properties at a fraction of the price investors paid a few years ago.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CNS" class="">Cohen &amp; Steers</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GS" class="">Goldman Sachs</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> EQT Exeter and BGO, formerly known as BentallGreenOak, are among the prominent names raising billions of dollars for funds to target distressed assets and other real estate with slumping values, according to regulatory filings.</p><p> “The last few weeks, I&#39;ve been saying, &#39;holy mackerel, they&#39;re coming out of the woodwork,&#39;” said Kevin Gannon, chief executive of Robert A. Stanger &amp; Co., an investment-banking firm that tracks real-estate fundraising. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=88CDF171-D046-4FD4-A4BB-72130DCCB4C6&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fwall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> With housing in short supply, developers are converting more empty offices into apartments. But not all buildings are candidates for reuse, even as more than one billion square feet of office space sits vacant across the US Photo Illustration: Amber Bragdon<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>The new funds are seeking to capitalize on one of the most troubled commercial-property markets in decades. Values have nosedived since interest rates spiked last year, driving up borrowing costs in the highly leveraged business. The office market, one of the largest sectors, has also been clobbered by a sluggish return-to-office rate, which has sent vacancy rates soaring. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-real-estate-haven-turns-perilous-with-roughly-1-trillion-coming-due-74d20528?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Apartment buildings</a> , an investor haven in the past, look vulnerable as owners try to refinance at much higher rates. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/local-malls-stuck-in-death-spiral-plunge-in-value-a7998b7d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">Mall owners are contending with</a> steep value declines, some of more than 70% over the past few years.</p><p> Commercial-property sales have been moribund until recently because most sellers haven&#39;t been willing to cut their prices to the levels that buyers are demanding. Now, a small but growing number of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/rise-in-distressed-sales-signals-new-chapter-for-beleaguered-office-market-bbff313c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">office owners have begun to capitulate</a> , unloading distressed properties.</p><p> The capitulation marks a new phase in the commercial real-estate upheaval, as more beleaguered property owners turn over properties to lenders or decide to take what they can get, rather than hold out hope for an eventual recovery. This wave of fundraising is the latest sign that sales activity is expected to increase as more sellers yield on price. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="827" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-834573?width=639&amp;height=827" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Developer Presidio Bay purchased a San Francisco office tower for $41 million, compared with its 2014 sales price of $107 million.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jeff Peters</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In one recent example, the owner of a downtown San Francisco office tower unloaded the property for $41 million to developer Presidio Bay. The seller, Clarion Partners, had purchased the property for $107 million in 2014.</p><p> While the clearest distress is in the office sector, many property owners with floating-rate debt may also feel pressured to sell at marked-down prices because they are unable to refinance at today&#39;s higher rates. In addition, fund managers expect values to fall as regional banks, under pressure from this year&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bank-collapse-crisis-timeline-724f6458?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">rash of bank failures</a> , unload commercial-property loan portfolios at discounted prices.</p><p> “There are selective opportunities beginning to arise for investors that are in a position to take advantage of weakness,” said Rich Hill,</p> head of real-estate strategy for Cohen &amp; Steers, which is aiming to raise more than $2.5 billion in a new nontraded real-estate investment trust.<p></p><p> Commercial-property values already have fallen about 10 to 15 percentage points from their peaks in the third quarter last year, and might fall a total of 20 to 25 percentage points, said Hill. “You have to go back to the [savings and loan] crisis and the global financial crisis to see such big declines in property valuations,” he said.</p><p> The volume of distressed commercial real estate grew by $8 billion in the second quarter, reflecting the rise in cases where the owners defaulted or lenders foreclosed, according to data provider MSCI Real Assets. That is the biggest quarterly increase since the second quarter of 2020.</p><p> While most of the new funds are looking to buy property, some are planning to lend to property owners and fill the void left by the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-lending-by-mortgage-reits-has-dried-up-49551878?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">cutback in activity</a> from regional banks and mortgage real-estate investment trusts. With less competition, the lenders who are still active are able to charge higher rates and get better deal terms from borrowers.</p><p> Invesco Real Estate, which has a long track record of raising funds from institutional investors for real-estate credit funds, is raising its first such fund targeting the retail audience.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Is commercial real estate undervalued right now?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Many of the new funds, such as those being raised by Invesco and Cohen &amp; Steers, are targeting individual investors. Smaller investors have shown an enormous appetite for property investments in recent years, especially with the growth of the nontraded real-estate investment trust industry which raised about $100 billion in the past seven years.</p><p> But many of the nontraded REITs that were formed before last year&#39;s rise in interest rates have been under pressure to redeem money back to investors who want to cash out. Over $9 billion was redeemed in the first six months of this year, according to Stanger, and many investors have been forced to wait to get their money because of the rush to the redemption door.</p><p> Still, the new funds will be facing a lot of competition from cash-rich funds aimed at institutions. Opportunistic real-estate funds run by private-equity firms have nearly $145 billion in so-called dry powder for future investments, up from $120 billion at the end of last year, according to data firm Preqin.</p><p> It is still possible that distressed opportunities won&#39;t arise if the US economy has <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/what-top-executives-are-saying-about-a-soft-landing-4daf9123?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a soft landing</a> , in which inflation is tamed by the Federal Reserve without tipping the economy into recession.</p><p> Sales volume will likely increase when debt markets stabilize and values become more clear. “Broadly speaking, people are waiting to see what the world looks like,” said Michael Stark, co-head of the PJT Park Hill Real Estate Group, a global advisory firm and placement agent. “They&#39;re waiting for motivated sellers.”</p><p> Write to Peter Grant at <a href="mailto:peter.grant@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">peter.grant@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 15 Aug 2023 04:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/wall-street-is-ready-to-scoop-up-commercial-real-estateon-the-cheap-6edac64f<author><![CDATA[Peter Grant]]></author><category> commercial re</category><category> Marine Transport</category><category> Trusts/Funds/Financial Vehicles</category><category> Investment Trusts</category><category> Real Estate Investment Trusts</category><category> Real Estate Services/Transactions</category><category> Freight Transport/Logistics</category><category> Commercial/Industrial Real Estate</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>Marine Freight</category><category>房地产</category><category>Water Transport/Shipping</category><category> Transportation/Logistics</category><category> Ownership Changes</category><category> Physical Asset Transactions</category><category> Corporate Actions</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>Commercial RE</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Cohen &amp; Steers</category><category> CNS</category><category> Goldman Sachs</category><category> GS</category><category> EQT Exeter</category><category> ownership changes</category><category> physical asset transactions</category><category> corporate actions</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>marine transport</category><category> trusts</category><category>资金</category><category>financial vehicles</category><category> investment trusts</category><category> real estate investment trusts</category><category> real estate services</category><category> transactions</category><category> freight transport</category><category> logistics</category><category> commercial</category><category> industrial real estate</category><category>房地产</category><category>建造</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>marine freight</category><category> water transport</category><category> shipping</category><category> transportation </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Argentina’s Financial Markets Plummet After Right-Wing Outsider Wins Primary Vote]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>哈维尔·米雷 (Javier Milei) 在 10 月总统选举前的初选中获得大部分选票后，央行贬值比索的官方汇率<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132905"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="486" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835118?width=860&amp;height=486" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">极右翼总统候选人哈维尔·米雷周日在布宜诺斯艾利斯的竞选总部发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：alejandro pagni/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001132905"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·杜贝</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/juan-forero" itemprop="url" rel="author">胡安·福雷罗</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 14 日下午 2:42（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>周一，阿根廷的美元债券暴跌，比索走弱，一天前，一位自由主义局外人在十月大选前将自己定位为该<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentine-presidential-primary-voters-propel-far-right-outsider-to-surprise-win-ec24e5b4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国的主要希望</a>。</p><p> 52 岁的经济学家哈维尔·米雷 (Javier Milei) 抱怨他所谓的“政治阶层”，他在周日的初选中获得的票数超过了中右翼“共同谋变”联盟和执政的庇隆主义运动的候选人经济，引发了骚乱。部长塞尔吉奥·马萨。</p><p>美国银行(Bank of America)新兴市场主权债务策略师卢卡斯·马丁(Lucas Martin)表示，阿根廷美元债券早盘下跌约14%，尽管最初的下意识反应几乎没有成交量。随着交易的进展，当天的损失减少了一半，至 7% 左右。央行将比索的官方汇率贬值，比索贬值超过20%，至1美元兑换350左右。布宜诺斯艾利斯街头的比索黑市汇率也出现贬值，跌幅超过 10%，至 1 美元兑换 690 比索左右。</p><p>投资者原本预计“共同谋变”联盟会在投票率较低的投票中表现更好。</p><p>芝加哥威廉·布莱尔投资管理公司的投资组合经理贾里德·卢表示：“低投票率和意外结果导致政治和市场不确定性增加。” “鉴于经济状况不佳，选民似乎要求变革。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=FDB4DFD7-9FD4-49A6-9874-2C3D318261D2&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fargentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">巴西和阿根廷领导人重新提出了共同货币的想法，以促进贸易并减少该地区对美元的依赖。 《华尔街日报》的萨曼莎·皮尔森解释了为什么它不太可能很快实施。照片：伊芙·哈特利<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>美国投资者撤离阿根廷股市，导致<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/ARGT" class="company-name">Global X MSCI 阿根廷 ETF</a>在周一早盘交易中下跌 6%，为一年多来最糟糕的一天奠定了基础。截至纽约中午，该基金当天交易价格下跌 2.4%。</p><p>米莱周一在接受电台采访时表示，他的胜利是对阿尔贝托·费尔南德斯总统政府的“一记沉重耳光”，阿尔贝托·费尔南德斯总统在一项民意调查中获得了 75% 的反对率，其任期将于 12 月结束。</p><p> “他们不知道如何解释从现在到 12 月他们将要做什么，”他在里瓦达维亚广播电台谈到费尔南德斯政府时说道。</p><p>米莱是一位民粹主义新贵，承诺关闭央行、用美元取代比索并削减支出，她获得了 30% 的选票。在 10 月份决定谁参加第一轮总统选举的选举中，米莱击败了帕特里夏·布尔里奇 (Patricia Bullrich)，后者是来自“共同促进变革”(Together for Change) 的严厉打击犯罪的保守派人士、前安全部长，得票率为 28.3%；马萨 (Massa) 的得票率被认为更高。中间派和商业比总统更友好。马萨获得了27.3%的选票。</p><p>这次投票是在一个正遭受<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1028667586359671120?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2001年金融危机</a>以来最严重经济危机的国家举行的。大约40%的阿根廷人现在生活在贫困之中。通货膨胀率高达 116%，导致家庭难以购买足够的食物，企业也难以正常运转。</p><p>米莱利用了沸腾的愤怒，向阿根廷人保证，如果他们通过关闭各部委来大幅缩减政府规模，该国将重新站稳脚跟。</p><p> “今天，我们站起来对这个颓废的模型说得够多了，”米莱周日晚些时候在欢呼的支持者面前说道。 “我邀请阿根廷人参与自由革命。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835300?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿根廷的通货膨胀率高达116%，导致家庭难以购买足够的食物。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Natacha Pisarenko/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>米莱的强劲表现引发了一场三向竞争，使他与两个传统政治联盟展开竞争。政治分析人士表示，保守派布尔里奇可能会成为他十月份最强劲的对手，因为庇隆主义者的强烈反对，在过去20年的大部分时间里，庇隆主义者的统治以慷慨的国家补贴和社会计划下<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/outgoing-argentine-president-to-leave-big-tab-for-successor-1449178707?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的公共支出急剧增加</a>为标志。</p><p>布尔里奇承认一些阿根廷人想要米莱，但他表示她也代表着变革。</p><p>布尔里奇公开表示：“米莱就是其中的代表，但我们也是如此。”他已承诺迅速采取行动削减财政赤字并取消货币管制。 “这一次，从这里到选举，我们以极大的热情代表这一变化，这一点非常重要。”</p><p>布尔里奇的联盟在时任总统毛里西奥·马克里 (Mauricio Macri) 的领导下于 2015 年至 2019 年执政。他试图在不引发社会动荡的情况下<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/gradualism-is-dead-argentina-faces-pressure-to-hasten-economic-overhaul-1527586201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">逐步减少前庇隆主义政府遗留下来的赤字</a>。随着政府承担了数十亿美元的债务并且<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-peso-plunges-to-record-low-1535578085?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">通货膨胀率飙升</a>，这一策略失败了。许多阿根廷人还没有忘记。</p><p></p>玛丽亚·科尔曼·罗德里格斯 (Maria Colman Rodríguez) 需要抚养三个孩子，但没有工作，她说她感觉“没有政客帮助我们”。<p></p><p> “我被他们所有人背叛了，”她说。 “他们都承诺一些事情，但没有兑现。”</p><p> “Milei 可能成为我们的希望，”她补充道。 “我们必须相信一个与众不同的人。”</p><p>这位候选人提出了经济学家认为阿根廷急需的一些处方，例如开放国家贸易、减税以及将国有企业私有化以抑制支出。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-835299?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">阿根廷正遭受二十多年来最严重的经济危机。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：路易斯·罗巴约/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>他还拥有截然不同的社会愿景：他承诺结束公立学校，支持人们出售器官的市场，提议扩大枪支获取范围并结束合法堕胎。</p><p>米莱承认，他对政治机构的尖锐攻击让一些阿根廷人望而却步。</p><p> “我说我的想法，”他去年说道。 “无论谁喜欢与否，我都按照我的自由主义原则行事和工作。”</p><p>但米雷作为总统可能在反对派控制的国会中得不到多少支持，他经常痛斥国会，这使得他雄心勃勃的改革很难通过。紧缩措施也可能面临强大工会和社会运动的强烈反对。</p><p>花旗研究部分析师在周一的一份研究报告中表示，米雷将经济美元化的提议引起了投资者的担忧，因为实施起来存在挑战。</p><p>报告称：“阿根廷没有流动储备，很难以债务或投资的形式获得资金。” “此外，这种破坏性的提议可能会面临政府的阻力。”</p><p>目前，阿根廷人面临着更多困难。经济学家表示，周一比索的疲软可能会导致通胀进一步走高。</p><p> “如果比索继续贬值 20%，未来几天我们将看到严重的通货膨胀，”咨询公司牛津经济研究院 (Oxford Economics) 负责拉丁美洲研究的经济学家费利佩·卡马戈 (Felipe Camargo) 表示。</p><p>经济学家福斯托·斯波托诺(Fausto Spotorno)表示，他和妻子一直在购买一辆新车，但当他们周一去供应商签署文件时，他们被告知，由于市场不确定性，销售被无限期搁置。</p><p> “公司、工厂就是不知道如何处理他们持有的库存，”斯波托诺说。 “我们正处于这样的境地，你不知道在经济上，事情是否会在未来 10 个月内得到解决。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Kejal Vyas、Eric Wallerstein 和 Silvina Frydlewsky 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé： <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 14 Aug 2023 18:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/argentinas-dollar-bonds-plummet-after-far-right-outsider-wins-primary-vote-b7ab9b72<author><![CDATA[Ryan DubéJuan Forero]]></author><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>货币/货币市场</category><category>外汇市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过